|{{sort|1973-10-31|October 31, 1973}}
|[[Mountjoy Jail]]
|{{flag|Ireland}}
| style="background-color: #CEF2CE;"| Yes
|{{sortname|JB|O'Hagan|nolink=1}}<br />
[[Seamus Twomey]]<br />Kevin Mallon
|On October 31, 1973 an [[Provisional Irish Republican Army|IRA]] member hijacked a helicopter and forced the pilot to land in the exercise yard of Dublin's [[Mountjoy Jail]]'s D Wing at 3:40&nbsp;p.m., October 31, 1973. Three members of the IRA were [[1973 Mountjoy Prison helicopter escape|able to escape]]: JB O'Hagan, [[Seamus Twomey]] and Kevin Mallon. Another prisoner who also was in the prison was quoted as saying, ''"One shamefaced screw apologised to the governor and said he thought it was the new Minister for Defence ([[Paddy Donegan]]) arriving. I told him it was our Minister of Defence leaving."''

The Mountjoy helicopter escape became [[Republican Movement (Ireland)|Republican lore]] and was immortalized by "[[The Helicopter Song]]", which contains the lines ''"It's up like a bird and over the city. There's three men a'missing I heard the warder say"''.<ref name="mountjoy">{{cite web | year = 2001 | url = http://republican-news.org/archive/2001/November01/01hist.html | title = Chopper escape from Mountjoy | publisher = [[Republican News]] | accessdate = May 14, 2009}}</ref>
