|{{sort|1983-01-31|January, 1983}}
|{{sort|Pentridge|[[HM Prison Pentridge|Pentridge (HM Prison)]]}}
|{{flag|Australia}}
| style="background-color: #F2CECE;"| No
|{{sortname|David|McMillan|David McMillan (smuggler)}}
|Arrests were made for the 1983 attempted helicopter escape from Melbourne’s Pentridge Prison in Australia.<ref name="melbournecrime">{{cite web |year=2007 |url = http://www.melbournecrime.bizhosting.com/david.mcmillan.htm|title = David Peter McMillan|publisher = melbourne crime| accessdate = May 15, 2009 | last= |quote= |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080505073611/http://www.melbournecrime.bizhosting.com/david.mcmillan.htm |archivedate = May 5, 2008}}</ref> The three, all held on drug-importation charges, had hired a former [[Special Air Service|SAS]] soldier, then living in the [[Philippines]], to lift the prisoners from the jail’s tennis court to a nearby van fitted with panels to hide them for the 600 kilometre road trip to Sydney, where a yacht was to take them to [[Manila]].
The plan was thwarted when [[Antony Moynihan, 3rd Baron Moynihan|Lord Tony Moynihan]], himself an exile in the Philippines, informed the [[Australian Federal Police]], who then ran it as a sting operation. Tony Moynihan would later become an informer against [[Howard Marks]] in a Florida trial.

Of the accused, only [[David McMillan (smuggler)|David McMillan]] and his accountant friend who had visited the prison stood trial. During the hearings, few prosecution witnesses used their real names as they were mostly from Moynihan’s former West African [[MI6]] unit. Those on trial were convicted and sentenced.<ref>[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]; Date: Jan 21, 1983</ref>
